{
  "text": "Many electronic databases are available to find reliable medical information, but none of these databases are comprehensive: for example, some articles are referenced in one unique database [CITATION_1] and others are only referenced in a few databases [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . These findings were also observed in occupational medicine and toxicology [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . As a result, researchers are recommended to search multiple databases when performing comprehensive articles research, an approach that is standard practice for conducting meta-analysis. Nevertheless, more hits do not necessarily mean higher quality studies.",
